      <exercise xml:id="whysqrt8is2sqrt2">
      <title>
        Why is <m>\sqrt{8}</m> equal to <m>2\sqrt{2}</m>?
      </title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          In <xref ref="fig-tripfsqrt8"/>, assume <m>DEFB</m> is a square 
          with side length <m>1</m> and that <m>F</m> and <m>D</m> are the midpoints  
          of <m>\overline{AB}</m> and <m>\overline{BC}</m>, respectively.
        </p>
        <figure xml:id="fig-tripfsqrt8">
          <caption>Right triangle of side length 2</caption>
          <image source="sqrt-of-8" width="66%">
            <description>
              Isosceles triangle ABC has side length 2. Segment FE joins 
              the midpoints of side AB and hypotenuse AC. Segment DE joins the 
              midpoints of side BC and hypotenuse AC.
            </description>
          </image>
        </figure>
        <p>
          Write a letter to Aunt Josephine or another friend in which you describe  
          how this picture shows that <m>\sqrt{8}=2\sqrt{2}.</m>
        </p>
        <aside>
          <p>Algebraically, we know <m>\sqrt{8}=\sqrt{4\cdot 2}=\sqrt{4}\cdot\sqrt{2}
            =2\sqrt{2}</m>. For this writing prompt, give a geometric proof.
          </p>
        </aside>
      </statement>
    </exercise>
